<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Castela emoryi </i>(a CNPS list 2.3 plant) is a large, leafless shrub that grows to 4 m in height; it has rigid, light green stems that end in stout thorns. Clusters of hard capsules, first yellowish then drying to black, persist on plants for up to 7 years. Seeds apparently require scarification of the seed coat to initiate germination (Shreve and Wiggins 1964, Turner at al. 1995). Regional manuals also use the name <i>Holacantha emoryi</i>. This plant is easily confused with <i>Ziziphus obtusifolia, </i>with its gray branches, and <i>Koeberlinia spinosa, </i>with its dark green branches and black berries. Known occurrences of <i>Castela emoryi </i>are scattered in California’s deserts, where summer rainfall is common, summer temperatures are hot, and frost is rare. We need further information to understand the relationships of this species in the state’s desert vegetation.<br/>
<br/>
Stands typically associate with fine substrate in washes or basins and are associated with <i>Ambrosia dumosa, Brickellia incana, Encelia virginensis, Ephedra californica, Larrea tridentata, </i>or other species of low-energy wash environments. Plot data are available from CNDDB (2008). </div>
</div>

    
	
	
